<!-- this is the content table -->

<tr><td valign="top"><div>

<font size="+4" color=#990000>In English</font> the direct object pronouns are:<br>



<table align="center" cellpadding=5 bgcolor="#E0F0F5" width="850">
<tr>
<td><div>She sees <font color="#3915B4"><strong>me</strong></font>.<br>
She sees <font color="#3915B4"><strong>you</strong></font>.<br>
She sees <font color="#3915B4"><strong>him / her / it</strong></font>.<br>
She sees <font color="#3915B4"><strong>us</strong></font>.<br>
She sees <font color="#3915B4"><strong>you (all)</strong></font>.<br>
She sees <font color="#3915B4"><strong>them</strong></font>.<br>
</div></td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
Note how they all receive the action of the verb <strong>directly</strong>. That's what makes them 
direct object pronouns.<br>
<br>
<font size="+4" color=#990000>In Spanish</font> the direct object pronouns are:<br>


<table align="center" cellpadding=5 bgcolor="#E0F0F5" width="850">
<tr>
<td width=50%><div>Ella <font color="#3915B4"><strong>me</strong></font> ve.<br>
Ella <font color="#3915B4"><strong>te</strong></font> ve.<br>
Ella <font color="#3915B4"><strong>lo / la </strong></font>ve.<br>
Ella <font color="#3915B4"><strong>nos</strong></font> ve.<br>
Ella <font color="#3915B4"><strong>os</strong></font> ve. <br>
Ella <font color="#3915B4"><strong>los / las</strong></font> ve.<br>
</div></td>

<td><div>
(for "yo")<br>
(for "t&uacute;")<br>
(for "usted, &eacute;l, ella")<br>
(for "nosotros, nosotras"<br>
(for "vosotros")<br>
(for "ustedes, ellos, ellas")<br>
</div></td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
Note the word order!
</div></td></tr>







